  "prompt": "How much does it cost to complete undergraduation in Purdue University as an International student?",
  "response": "The cost of completing an undergraduate degree at Purdue University for international students can vary depending on several factors, including the specific program of study, housing choices, meal plans, and personal expenses. As of the most recent data available (2023-2024 academic year), here\u2019s a general breakdown of the costs:\n\n### 1. **Tuition and Fees**\n   - **Tuition**: Approximately **$45,954 per year** (for full-time undergraduate students in most programs).\n   - **Fees**: Additional fees can total around **$1,200 to $1,500 per year** (including technology, activity, and health service fees).\n\n### 2. **Room and Board**\n   - **On-Campus Housing**: Approximately **$10,000 to $12,000 per year** (depending on the residence hall and room type).\n   - **Meal Plan**: Around **$5,000 to $6,000 per year** (depending on the plan selected).\n\n### 3. **Books and Supplies**\n   - Estimated at **$1,000 to $1,500 per year**.\n\n### 4. **Personal Expenses and Transportation**\n   - Personal expenses (clothing, entertainment, etc.): **$1,500 to $2,000 per year**.\n   - Transportation: **$500 to $1,000 per year** (depending on travel needs).\n\n### 5. **Health Insurance**\n   - International students are required to have health insurance, which costs approximately **$2,500 per year** (unless covered by a comparable plan).\n\n### **Total Estimated Cost**\nThe total estimated cost for one academic year ranges from **$66,454 to $69,954**. Over four years, this could amount to **$265,816 to $279,816**, depending on inflation and changes in tuition or fees.\n\n### Additional Notes:\n- Purdue University offers scholarships for international students, which can significantly reduce the cost.\n- Off-campus housing and budget-conscious living can also lower expenses.\n\nFor the most accurate and updated information, check Purdue University\u2019s official website or contact the Office of International Students and Scholars (ISS).",
  "temperature": 1.0,
